{
    "analysis": "Previous step loaded all four telemetry files into kernel variables and returned an overview (row counts, time ranges, top combos). We have the raw data in memory (metric_df, trace_df, log_df, error_logs_df). Next we must follow the preprocessing rules: compute global thresholds for each component-KPI time series using the full available series BEFORE filtering to the incident window. We should produce compact threshold tables (P95 and P5) for metric, trace and log KPIs so we can then detect anomalies inside the incident window efficiently.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For metric_df, trace_df, and log_df (use kpi_name, trace_name, log_name respectively), compute global P95 and P5 thresholds for each (cmdb_id, name_field) using the full available rows (do NOT filter by time). Store the thresholds in kernel variables (metric_thresholds, trace_thresholds, log_thresholds).\nReturn a compact JSON-friendly list of the top 20 (by total row count) (cmdb_id, name_field) groups for each of the three files with these fields: cmdb_id, name_field, count, p95, p5. Limit numeric precision to 6 decimals. Do NOT filter by the incident time window in this step. Keep outputs compact and store full thresholds in kernel for next steps."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous step we computed global thresholds and filtered telemetry to the incident window (2022-03-20 12:00:00–12:30:00). The incident-filtered tables show widespread anomalies: many metric and trace series have all points flagged as anomalous (either >=P95 or <=P5) and many pods show log.error_count anomalies (though their p95==0 making severity undefined). To progress to fault identification we must convert these per-point anomalies into consecutive anomalous sub-series (faults), filter out isolated spikes, and rank faults by severity and duration to find the likely root causes for the two failures. We should first extract the top candidate faults from metrics (fastest way to narrow components).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the incident-filtered metric_incident_df (already in kernel), identify consecutive anomalous subsequences (faults) for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) where a point is anomalous if value >= p95 OR value <= p5. Define consecutive as successive timestamps with difference equal to the sampling interval (use actual timestamp differences in the data).\nFor each fault (i.e., a maximal consecutive anomalous subsequence) compute and store these fields: cmdb_id, kpi_name, fault_start_ts (first timestamp), fault_end_ts (last timestamp), points (number of points), max_value, min_value, p95, p5, max_severity = max(value / p95) for points with p95>0 else NaN, min_severity = max(p5 / value) for points with value>0 else NaN, earliest_anomaly_ts (same as fault_start_ts).\nFilter out faults that are single-point spikes (points == 1) to remove isolated noise.\nReturn a compact list of the top 20 faults sorted primarily by max_severity (descending), secondarily by points (descending). For each returned fault row include the fields above and also a short sample of up to the first 3 timestamps in that fault (as a list). Keep numeric precision to 6 decimals. Store the full faults table in kernel variable metric_faults for next steps. Do not print raw time series—only the aggregated fault rows (<=20)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We previously computed metric-level faults and found a huge concentration of faults starting at 1647748800 (12:00:00 Asia/Shanghai) plus many smaller clusters at subsequent timestamps. The metric_faults table contains per-fault severity and start times. To identify the two failure events we should pick the most prominent fault-start clusters (by number of faults) within the 12:00–12:30 window and then find the top faulty components within each cluster. After that we will use traces and logs to further localize the most-downstream faulty component and the root-cause resource reason. The immediate next step is therefore to (1) list the top fault-start clusters by fault_count and (2) for the two largest clusters, summarize the top candidate cmdb_ids by count of faults and by severity to narrow root-cause candidates.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the kernel variables fault_start_clusters and metric_faults do the following and return JSON-serializable compact results:\n1) Return the top 10 fault_start_ts sorted by fault_count DESC with fields: fault_start_ts, fault_count, distinct_cmdb_count, example_cmdb_ids (up to 10).\n2) For the top 2 fault_start_ts (by fault_count), for each cluster return an aggregated list of the top 10 cmdb_id candidates sorted by number of faults within that cluster (descending). For each cmdb_id include these fields: fault_start_ts (cluster ts), cmdb_id, faults_in_cluster (count), distinct_kpi_count (number of different kpi_name values in those faults), max_max_severity (max of max_severity among that cmdb_id's faults, 6-decimal), avg_max_severity (mean of max_severity, 6-decimal), earliest_fault_start_ts (minimum fault_start_ts among that cmdb_id's faults; should equal cluster ts). Also include for each cmdb_id a short sample list (up to 3) of the worst kpi_name(s) with their max_severity values (kpi_name and its max_severity).\nLimit rows to top 10 cmdb_ids per cluster. Keep numeric precision to 6 decimals. Store results in kernel variables top_clusters_by_count and top_candidates_per_cluster for next steps."
}

